{"title_page": "Jagat Shiromani Temple, Amer", "text_new": "{{expert needed|1=India|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox Mandir\n| name               = Jagat Shiromani Temple\n| image              = Sri Jagat Siromani ji temple.JPG\n| alt          = Mehandipur Balaji deity\n| caption            = \n| map_type        = India Rajasthan#India\n| map_caption        = Location in, Rajasthan\n| coordinates        = {{coord|26.59|N|75.51|E|type:landmark_region:IN_scale:100|display=inline,title}}\n| other_names        = \n| proper_name        =\n \n \n \n \n \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Rajasthan]]\n| district           =\n| location           = \n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = [[Vishnu]]\n| temple_quantity  = \n| creator            = \n| website            = [http://www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in/images/Jaipur/jagatshiromani.htm Temples Government Webpage]\n}}\n'''Jagat Shiromani''' is a [[Hindu temple]] situated in [[Amer, India|Amer,]] India.<ref name=\"Amerjaipur\">{{Cite web|title = Jagat Shiromani Temple -Amer-jaipur|url = http://amerjaipur.in/Amer-monuments-description.php?mid=5&name=Jagat%20Shiromani%20Temple|website = amerjaipur.in|accessdate = 2015-09-26|first = Amit kumar pareek and Agam kumar|last = pareek}}</ref> This temple is dedicated to the Hindu gods [[Meera|Meera bai]], [[Krishna]] and [[Vishnu Purana|Vishnu]]. It was constructed between 1599-1608 AD by Queen Kanakwati,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Temple Profile|url = http://www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in/images/Jaipur/jagatshiromani.htm|website = www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in|accessdate = 2015-09-26}}</ref> who was the wife of King [[Man Singh I]] The temple was built in the memory of their son Jagat Singh.<ref name=\"Amerjaipur\" />\n\n== History ==\nThe temple is considered to be an important part of local history within Amer Town. The temple contains a statue of Krishna which has significance to the Hindu faith. According to religious doctrines the statue is the same statue that Meera Bai worshipped in the State of Mewar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travel|first1=Vibrant4|title=Famous Shri Jagat Shiromani temple in Amer Jaipur|url=http://travel.vibrant4.com/2016/02/famous-shri-jagat-shiromani-temple-in.html|website=Vibrant4Travel|accessdate=1 March 2016|ref=4}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Outer view of the Jagat Shiromani Temple.jpg|Outer view of the Jagat Shiromani Temple\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n{{commonscat|Sri Jagat Siromani Temple}}\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Rajasthan]]\n", "text_old": "{{expert needed|1=India|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox Mandir\n| name               = Jagat Shiromani Temple\n| image              = Sri Jagat Siromani ji temple.JPG\n| alt          = Mehandipur Balaji deity\n| caption            = \n| map_type        = India Rajasthan#India\n| map_caption        = Location in, Rajasthan\n| coordinates        = {{coord|26.59|N|75.51|E|type:landmark_region:IN_scale:100|display=inline,title}}\n| other_names        = \n| proper_name        =\n \n \n \n \n \n| country            = [[India]]\n| state              = [[Rajasthan]]\n| district           =\n| location           = \n| elevation_m        = \n| deity      = [[Vishnu]]\n| temple_quantity  = \n| creator            = \n| website            = [http://www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in/images/Jaipur/jagatshiromani.htm Temples Government Webpage]\n}}\n'''Jagat Shiromani''' is a [[Hindu temple]] situated in [[Amer, India|Amer,]] India.<ref name=\"Amerjaipur\">{{Cite web|title = Jagat Shiromani Temple -Amer-jaipur|url = http://amerjaipur.in/Amer-monuments-description.php?mid=5&name=Jagat%20Shiromani%20Temple|website = amerjaipur.in|accessdate = 2015-09-26|first = Amit kumar pareek and Agam kumar|last = pareek}}</ref> This temple is dedicated to the Hindu gods [[Meera|Meera bai]], [[Krishna]] and [[Vishnu Purana|Vishnu]]. It was constructed between 1599-1608 AD by Queen Kanakwati,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Temple Profile|url = http://www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in/images/Jaipur/jagatshiromani.htm|website = www.devasthan.rajasthan.gov.in|accessdate = 2015-09-26}}</ref> who was the wife of King Man Singh 1st. The temple was built in the memory of their son Jagat Singh.<ref name=\"Amerjaipur\" />\n\n== History ==\nThe temple is considered to be an important part of local history within Amer Town. The temple contains a statue of Krishna which has significance to the Hindu faith. According to religious doctrines the statue is the same statue that Meera Bai worshipped in the State of Mewar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Travel|first1=Vibrant4|title=Famous Shri Jagat Shiromani temple in Amer Jaipur|url=http://travel.vibrant4.com/2016/02/famous-shri-jagat-shiromani-temple-in.html|website=Vibrant4Travel|accessdate=1 March 2016|ref=4}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Outer view of the Jagat Shiromani Temple.jpg|Outer view of the Jagat Shiromani Temple\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />\n{{commonscat|Sri Jagat Siromani Temple}}\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Rajasthan]]\n", "name_user": "Kushagra666", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jagat_Shiromani_Temple,_Amer"}
{"title_page": "1017 Records", "text_new": " \n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = 1017 Records\n| image = 1017RecordsLogo.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = A silhouette of a flying bird over the vertically stacked words \"1017 Brick Squad\". The bird and the words are entirely black.\n| founded = {{start date|2007}}\n| founder = [[Gucci Mane]]\n| distributor = Alamo, [[EMPIRE Distribution]]\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[Trap music|trap]]\n| country = U.S.\n| location = Atlanta, Georgia\n| website = {{URL|1017BrickSquad.com}}\n}}\n\n'''1017 Records''', also known as '''1017 Eskimo''' and '''1017 Bricksquad''', is an American record label founded by [[Gucci Mane]] after his departure from Mizay Entertainment and the closing of So Icey. The label is home to Hoodrixh Miko, [[Hoodrich Pablo Juan]], and [[Ralo (rapper)|Ralo.]]3456\n\n==History==\n\n===2007\u201313===\nGucci Mane founded his first record independent label, So Icey Entertainment, after signing with Mizay Entertainment in 2007. Soon after Gucci released his [[independent album]], ''Trap-A-Thon''. On May 4, 2010, Gucci Mane announced he was closing So Icey Entertainment and left Mizay Entertainment due to business concerns with Debra Antney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11174/title.gucci-mane-leaves-so-icey-entertainment-for-brick-squad-1017|title=Gucci Mane Leaves So Icey Entertainment For Brick Squad 1017|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|date=May 5, 2010|publisher=Hip Hop DX|accessdate=October 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507083000/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11174/title.gucci-mane-leaves-so-icey-entertainment-for-brick-squad-1017|archive-date=May 7, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGucci Mane stated that he was starting his own record label and that his employer, Jerry Alvarado, was already signing a distribution deal with [[Asylum Records]]. The first artists to sign up to ''1017 Brick Squad'' were [[OJ Da Juiceman]], and [[Waka Flocka Flame]], who signed up whilst they were still signed to Mizay Entertainment.\n\nJuiceman's debut album was unofficially released through the Brick Squad record label (officially it was released through Asylum Records and Mizay Entertainment). Brick Squad's first mainstream success occurred in 2009, when Gucci released ''[[The State vs. Radric Davis]]''. Brick Squad also signed [[Waka Flocka Flame]], who released his debut album, ''[[Flockaveli]]'', through Brick Squad, Mizay Entertainment, and [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] On September 28, 2010, Mane released his seventh studio album, ''[[The Appeal: Georgia's Most Wanted]]''.\n\nOn December 16, 2011, member Slim Dunkin was shot and killed at an [[Atlanta]] recording studio preparing to shoot a music video. Slim Dunkin was shot while arguing with another person in the building, who has been identified as Atlanta rapper, Young Vito.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2011/12/16/emerging-waka-flocka-affiliate-slim-dunkin-dead/|title=AllHipHop \u00bb  Emerging Waka Flocka Affiliate Slim Dunkin Dead|work=AllHipHop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegrio.com/entertainment/slim-dunkin-murder-police-identify-a-suspect.php|title=Slim Dunkin murder: Police identify a suspect|work=theGrio}}</ref> On February 25, 2013, Young Vito was acquitted of murdering Slim Dunkin, but he was given a 25-year sentence for aggravated assault and possession of a firearm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2013/02/25/young-vito-acquitted-of-murder/|title=Young Vito Acquitted Of Slim Dunkin Murder - Rap Radar|work=Rap Radar}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016===\nOn March 15, 2013, via [[Twitter]], Gucci Mane tweeted that he \"dropped\" Waka Flocka Flame and he was no longer a member of 1017 Brick Squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23220/title.gucci-mane-drops-waka-flocka-flame-from-1017-brick-squad-|title=Gucci Mane Drops Waka Flocka Flame From 1017 Brick Squad|author=HipHopDX|date=March 15, 2013|work=HipHopDX|access-date=March 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527191333/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23220/title.gucci-mane-drops-waka-flocka-flame-from-1017-brick-squad-|archive-date=May 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The next day, Gucci's management claimed his Twitter account was hacked and he did not send the tweet about Waka Flocka.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gucci Mane\u2019s Management Claims His Twitter Account Was Hacked|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/03/gucci-manes-management-claims-his-twitter-account-was-hacked/|publisher=XXL|accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref> However Waka would claim this to be false and later diss Gucci Mane at a [[The Diplomats|Dipset]] reunion concert in New York City. On March 27, 2013, Waka told [[MTV]] that it would be impossible for him to be dropped from 1017 Brick Squad as he owns stake in the company. He also confirmed that there was indeed a feud going on between the rappers and \"they would never make music or do business together again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23375/title.waka-flocka-flame-confirms-gucci-mane-beef-vows-to-never-do-business-again|title=Waka Flocka Flame Confirms Gucci Mane Beef, Vows To Never Do Business Again|author=HipHopDX|date=March 28, 2013|work=HipHopDX|access-date=March 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527162929/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23375/title.waka-flocka-flame-confirms-gucci-mane-beef-vows-to-never-do-business-again|archive-date=May 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2013, various members of 1017 Brick Squad and Brick Squad Monopoly argued back and forth on Twitter. This was the culmination of a label-wide breakdown in communication, which included underlying labels like Mizay Entertainment and spawned Brick Squad Mafia, the label run by [[Mack Drama]] which is where Frenchie first ended up after splitting from the primary group, along with multiple other Brick Squad Artists. <ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.hip-hopvibe.com/2012/08/21/hhv-exclusive-mack-drama-talks-running-brick-squad-mafia-current-roster-and-future-plans/ | title=Mack Drama Talks Running Brick Squad Mafia}}</ref> [[Mack Drama]] is also famous for being the key to Flocka's street credibility, when he had the young rapper fly out to meet up with fellow OG Elm Street Pirus, a nod by the gang in its original location and by its original founding members, of approval for Flocka's repping of the gang. [[Mack Drama]] and [[Waka Flocka]] have since parted ways from one another, as the former sided with [[Gucci Mane]] in the greater dispute within the label. He then went on to be the driving force behind artists like \"Vee tha Rula\" (later signed to [[Kid Ink]] and [[Delyric Oracle]] signed to both his label and her own. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prlog.org/12708595-2018-2nd-quarter-executive-artist-roster-update-1017-bsm-mafia-gang-mdr.html|title=2018 2nd Quarter Executive & Artist Roster Update 1017 BSM MAFIA GANG MDR|first=1017 Mack Drama|last=Records|website=PRLog}}</ref> including Gucci Mane, Waka Flocka, Frenchie, Wooh da Kid, and OJ da Juiceman. Gucci would go on to say \"fuck brick squad\" and accuse his former manager, Waka Flocka's mom Debra Antney, of stealing money from OJ da Juiceman and [[Frenchie]]. Frenchie also accused Gucci Mane of paying for Young Vito's lawyer, the accused murderer of former 1017 Brick Squad artist Slim Dunkin, which Gucci denied. Frenchie would release a diss record towards Gucci the following day.<ref name=\"complex.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/gucci-mane-waka-flocka-flame-end-brick-squad-on-twitter|title=Brick Squad Might Be Finished as Gucci Mane, Waka Flocka Flame, and Others Trade Twitter Attacks|author=Dharmic X|work=Complex}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present===\nUpon Gucci Mane's latest incarceration release he created a new record label, 1017 Eskimo, a partner venture with Alamo/EMPIRE Distribution . Current artists signed to 1017 include Hoodrich Pablo Juan and Lil Wop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/08/gucci-mane-signs-hoodrich-pablo-juan-lil-wop/|title=Gucci Mane Signs Hoodrich Pablo Juan and Lil Wop to 1017 Eskimos - XXL|website=XXL Mag|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n===Current artists===\n*[[Gucci Mane]]\n*Z-Money<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/03/08/zmoney-ztm-gucci-mane-1017-interview|title=How ZMoney bounced back|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n==== 1017 Eskimo ====\n*[[Yung Mal]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/04/yung-mal-lil-quill-shot-tennessee/|title=Yung Mal and Lil Quill Shot After Performance in Nashville - XXL|first=C. Vernon Coleman|last=II|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n*Hoodrixh Miko <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Lil Quill]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American independent record labels]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rap record labels]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Warner Music Group]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues record labels]]\n", "text_old": " \n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name = 1017 Records\n| image = 1017RecordsLogo.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_alt = A silhouette of a flying bird over the vertically stacked words \"1017 Brick Squad\". The bird and the words are entirely black.\n| founded = {{start date|2007}}\n| founder = [[Gucci Mane]]\n| distributor = Alamo, [[EMPIRE Distribution]]\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[Trap music|trap]]\n| country = U.S.\n| location = Atlanta, Georgia\n| website = {{URL|1017BrickSquad.com}}\n}}\n\n'''1017 Records''', also known as '''1017 Eskimo''' and '''1017 Bricksquad''', is an American record label founded by [[Gucci Mane]] after his departure from Mizay Entertainment and the closing of So Icey. The label is home to Hoodrixh Miko, [[Hoodrich Pablo Juan]], and [[Ralo (rapper)|Ralo.]]\n\n==History==\n\n===2007\u201313===\nGucci Mane founded his first record independent label, So Icey Entertainment, after signing with Mizay Entertainment in 2007. Soon after Gucci released his [[independent album]], ''Trap-A-Thon''. On May 4, 2010, Gucci Mane announced he was closing So Icey Entertainment and left Mizay Entertainment due to business concerns with Debra Antney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11174/title.gucci-mane-leaves-so-icey-entertainment-for-brick-squad-1017|title=Gucci Mane Leaves So Icey Entertainment For Brick Squad 1017|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|date=May 5, 2010|publisher=Hip Hop DX|accessdate=October 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507083000/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11174/title.gucci-mane-leaves-so-icey-entertainment-for-brick-squad-1017|archive-date=May 7, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGucci Mane stated that he was starting his own record label and that his employer, Jerry Alvarado, was already signing a distribution deal with [[Asylum Records]]. The first artists to sign up to ''1017 Brick Squad'' were [[OJ Da Juiceman]], and [[Waka Flocka Flame]], who signed up whilst they were still signed to Mizay Entertainment.\n\nJuiceman's debut album was unofficially released through the Brick Squad record label (officially it was released through Asylum Records and Mizay Entertainment). Brick Squad's first mainstream success occurred in 2009, when Gucci released ''[[The State vs. Radric Davis]]''. Brick Squad also signed [[Waka Flocka Flame]], who released his debut album, ''[[Flockaveli]]'', through Brick Squad, Mizay Entertainment, and [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] On September 28, 2010, Mane released his seventh studio album, ''[[The Appeal: Georgia's Most Wanted]]''.\n\nOn December 16, 2011, member Slim Dunkin was shot and killed at an [[Atlanta]] recording studio preparing to shoot a music video. Slim Dunkin was shot while arguing with another person in the building, who has been identified as Atlanta rapper, Young Vito.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/2011/12/16/emerging-waka-flocka-affiliate-slim-dunkin-dead/|title=AllHipHop \u00bb  Emerging Waka Flocka Affiliate Slim Dunkin Dead|work=AllHipHop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegrio.com/entertainment/slim-dunkin-murder-police-identify-a-suspect.php|title=Slim Dunkin murder: Police identify a suspect|work=theGrio}}</ref> On February 25, 2013, Young Vito was acquitted of murdering Slim Dunkin, but he was given a 25-year sentence for aggravated assault and possession of a firearm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2013/02/25/young-vito-acquitted-of-murder/|title=Young Vito Acquitted Of Slim Dunkin Murder - Rap Radar|work=Rap Radar}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016===\nOn March 15, 2013, via [[Twitter]], Gucci Mane tweeted that he \"dropped\" Waka Flocka Flame and he was no longer a member of 1017 Brick Squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23220/title.gucci-mane-drops-waka-flocka-flame-from-1017-brick-squad-|title=Gucci Mane Drops Waka Flocka Flame From 1017 Brick Squad|author=HipHopDX|date=March 15, 2013|work=HipHopDX|access-date=March 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527191333/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23220/title.gucci-mane-drops-waka-flocka-flame-from-1017-brick-squad-|archive-date=May 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The next day, Gucci's management claimed his Twitter account was hacked and he did not send the tweet about Waka Flocka.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gucci Mane\u2019s Management Claims His Twitter Account Was Hacked|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/03/gucci-manes-management-claims-his-twitter-account-was-hacked/|publisher=XXL|accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref> However Waka would claim this to be false and later diss Gucci Mane at a [[The Diplomats|Dipset]] reunion concert in New York City. On March 27, 2013, Waka told [[MTV]] that it would be impossible for him to be dropped from 1017 Brick Squad as he owns stake in the company. He also confirmed that there was indeed a feud going on between the rappers and \"they would never make music or do business together again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23375/title.waka-flocka-flame-confirms-gucci-mane-beef-vows-to-never-do-business-again|title=Waka Flocka Flame Confirms Gucci Mane Beef, Vows To Never Do Business Again|author=HipHopDX|date=March 28, 2013|work=HipHopDX|access-date=March 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527162929/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23375/title.waka-flocka-flame-confirms-gucci-mane-beef-vows-to-never-do-business-again|archive-date=May 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2013, various members of 1017 Brick Squad and Brick Squad Monopoly argued back and forth on Twitter. This was the culmination of a label-wide breakdown in communication, which included underlying labels like Mizay Entertainment and spawned Brick Squad Mafia, the label run by [[Mack Drama]] which is where Frenchie first ended up after splitting from the primary group, along with multiple other Brick Squad Artists. <ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.hip-hopvibe.com/2012/08/21/hhv-exclusive-mack-drama-talks-running-brick-squad-mafia-current-roster-and-future-plans/ | title=Mack Drama Talks Running Brick Squad Mafia}}</ref> [[Mack Drama]] is also famous for being the key to Flocka's street credibility, when he had the young rapper fly out to meet up with fellow OG Elm Street Pirus, a nod by the gang in its original location and by its original founding members, of approval for Flocka's repping of the gang. [[Mack Drama]] and [[Waka Flocka]] have since parted ways from one another, as the former sided with [[Gucci Mane]] in the greater dispute within the label. He then went on to be the driving force behind artists like \"Vee tha Rula\" (later signed to [[Kid Ink]] and [[Delyric Oracle]] signed to both his label and her own. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prlog.org/12708595-2018-2nd-quarter-executive-artist-roster-update-1017-bsm-mafia-gang-mdr.html|title=2018 2nd Quarter Executive & Artist Roster Update 1017 BSM MAFIA GANG MDR|first=1017 Mack Drama|last=Records|website=PRLog}}</ref> including Gucci Mane, Waka Flocka, Frenchie, Wooh da Kid, and OJ da Juiceman. Gucci would go on to say \"fuck brick squad\" and accuse his former manager, Waka Flocka's mom Debra Antney, of stealing money from OJ da Juiceman and [[Frenchie]]. Frenchie also accused Gucci Mane of paying for Young Vito's lawyer, the accused murderer of former 1017 Brick Squad artist Slim Dunkin, which Gucci denied. Frenchie would release a diss record towards Gucci the following day.<ref name=\"complex.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/09/gucci-mane-waka-flocka-flame-end-brick-squad-on-twitter|title=Brick Squad Might Be Finished as Gucci Mane, Waka Flocka Flame, and Others Trade Twitter Attacks|author=Dharmic X|work=Complex}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present===\nUpon Gucci Mane's latest incarceration release he created a new record label, 1017 Eskimo, a partner venture with Alamo/EMPIRE Distribution . Current artists signed to 1017 include Hoodrich Pablo Juan and Lil Wop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/08/gucci-mane-signs-hoodrich-pablo-juan-lil-wop/|title=Gucci Mane Signs Hoodrich Pablo Juan and Lil Wop to 1017 Eskimos - XXL|website=XXL Mag|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n===Current artists===\n*[[Gucci Mane]]\n*Z-Money<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/03/08/zmoney-ztm-gucci-mane-1017-interview|title=How ZMoney bounced back|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n==== 1017 Eskimo ====\n*[[Yung Mal]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/04/yung-mal-lil-quill-shot-tennessee/|title=Yung Mal and Lil Quill Shot After Performance in Nashville - XXL|first=C. Vernon Coleman|last=II|website=XXL Mag|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n*Hoodrixh Miko <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Lil Quill]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:American independent record labels]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rap record labels]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Warner Music Group]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2007]]\n[[Category:Rhythm and blues record labels]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1007:b115:ffa:9406:27ac:db5:f7ff", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Yuo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1017_Records"}
{"title_page": "Boyd massacre", "text_new": "[[File:Louis John Steel - The blowing up of the Boyd Steele (1889).jpg|thumb|right|300px|''The Blowing Up of the Boyd'' by [[Louis John Steele]], 1889]]\nThe '''''Boyd'' massacre''' occurred in December 1809 when [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] residents of [[Whangaroa Harbour]] in northern [[New Zealand]] killed and ate between 66 and 70 Europeans.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419 , ''The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser, 8 May 1832, retrieved 4 July 2011]</ref> This is reputedly the highest number of Europeans killed by M\u0101ori in a single event in New Zealand, and the incident is also one of the bloodiest instances of [[cannibalism]] on record. The massacre is thought to have been in revenge for the whipping of a young M\u0101ori chief<ref name=\"nzhistory.net.nz\">[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident New Zealand History Online, ''The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?'' Retrieved 3 May 2011]</ref> by the crew of the sailing ship ''[[Boyd (1783 ship)|Boyd]]''.\n\nIn retribution, European whalers attacked the island [[P\u0101 (M\u0101ori)|pa]] of chief [[Te Pahi]] about 60&nbsp;km south-east<!--bearing from boyd site to te pahi island is 115 deg-->,<ref name=\"teara.govt.nz\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t53/1?setlang=en The Encyclopedia Of New Zealand, ''Dictionary of New Zealand Biography'', TePahi, retrieved 21 May 2011]</ref><ref name=\"nzhistory.net.nz\"/> in the mistaken belief that he ordered the killings. Between 16 and 60 Maori and one European died in the clash.<ref name=\"teara.govt.nz\"/><ref name=\"trove.nla.gov.au\">http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page6631?zoomLevel=2</ref> News of the events delayed the first missionary visits to the country, and caused the number of shipping visits to fall to \"almost nothing\" over the next few years.\n\n==Background==\nThe ''[[Boyd (1783 ship)|Boyd]]'' was a 395-ton ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]]) [[brigantine]] [[convict ship]] that sailed in October 1809 from Australia's [[Sydney Cove]] to [[Whangaroa]] on the east coast of New Zealand's [[Northland Peninsula]] to pick up [[kauri]] [[Spar (sailing)|spar]]s. She was under the command of Captain [[John Thompson (ship captain)|John Thompson]] and carried about 70 people.\n\nThe ship carried several passengers, including ex-convicts who had completed their transportation sentences and four or five New Zealanders who were returning to their homeland. Among the latter was Te Ara, or Tarrah, known to the crew as George, the son of a [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] [[Tribal chief|chief]] from Whangaroa. Te Ara had spent more than a year on board different vessels that included a sealing expedition to islands in the [[Southern Ocean]].\n\nOn the ''Boyd'' he was expected to work his passage on the ship. Some accounts state that he declined to do so because he was ill or because of his status as a chief's son.<ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\">{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2003-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609212225/http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html |archive-date=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Shipwrecks and Disasters at Sea W.H.G. Kingston. George Routledge and Sons, London. 1873</ref> Another account states that the ship's cook accidentally threw some [[pewter]] spoons overboard and accused Te Ara of stealing them to avoid being flogged himself.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419 The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser, May 1832, page 4]</ref> [[Alexander Berry]], in a letter describing the events, said: \"The captain had been rather too hasty in resenting some slight theft.\"<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/11933/11933-h/11933-h.htm#CHAPTER_XI A NARRATIVE OF A NINE MONTHS' RESIDENCE IN NEW ZEALAND CHAPTER XI]</ref>\n\nWhatever the reason, the result was that the captain deprived him of food and had him tied to a [[capstan (nautical)|capstan]] and whipped.<ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\"/>\n\nThis treatment of Te Ara prompted him to seek ''[[utu (M\u0101ori concept)|utu]]'', or revenge. Te Ara regained the confidence of the captain and persuaded him to put into Whangaroa Bay, assuring him that it was the best place to secure the timber he desired.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUpon reaching Whangaroa, Te Ara reported his indignities to his tribe and displayed the whip marks on his back. In accordance with M\u0101ori customs, they formed a plan for ''utu''. Under British law, whipping was the common punishment for minor crimes - A British person could be legally hanged for stealing goods to the value of 5 shillings. In M\u0101ori culture, however, the son of a chief was a privileged figure who did not bow to an outsider's authority. Physical punishment of his son caused the chief to suffer a loss of face (or \"[[mana]]\"), and to M\u0101ori this warranted a violent retribution.\n\n==Killings==\nThree days after the ''Boyd's'' arrival, the M\u0101ori invited Captain Thompson to follow their canoes to find suitable kauri trees. Thompson, his chief officer and three others followed the canoes to the entrance of the [[Kaeo River]]. The remaining crew stayed aboard with the passengers, preparing the vessel for the voyage to England.\n\nWhen the boats were beyond the ''Boyd's'' sight the M\u0101ori attacked the [[p\u0101keh\u0101]] (foreigners), killing them all with clubs and axes. The M\u0101ori stripped the western clothes from the victims and a group donned them as disguise. Another group carried the bodies to their [[p\u0101 (M\u0101ori)|p\u0101]] (village) to be eaten.<ref name=\"NZHistory\">[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?], New Zealand History Online, Ministry for Culture and Heritage. Updated 2008-01-24. Accessed 2008-05-05.</ref>\n\nAt dusk the disguised group manned the longboat, and at nightfall they slipped alongside the ''Boyd'' and were greeted by the crew. Other M\u0101ori canoes awaited the signal to attack. The first to die was a ship's officer: the attackers then crept around the deck, stealthily killing all the crew. The passengers were called to the deck and then killed. Five people hid up the mast among the rigging, where they witnessed the dismembering of their friends and colleagues' bodies below.\n\nThe next morning the survivors saw a large canoe carrying chief [[Te Pahi]] from the Bay of Islands enter the harbour. The chief had come to the area to trade with the Whangaroa M\u0101ori. The Europeans called out to Te Pahi's canoe for help. After Te Pahi had gathered the survivors from the ''Boyd'', they headed for shore. But two Whangaroa canoes pursued them. As the survivors fled along the beach, Te Pahi watched as all but one were caught and killed by the pursuers.\n\n==European survivors==\n\nFive people were spared in the [[massacre]]: Ann Morley and her baby, in a cabin; apprentice Thomas Davis (or Davison), hidden in the hold; the second mate; and two-year-old Betsy Broughton, taken by a local chief who put a feather in her hair and kept her for three weeks before rescue. The second mate was killed and eaten when his usefulness in making fish-hooks was exhausted.<ref name=\"NZHistory\"/>\n\n==Destruction of the ''Boyd''==\nThe Whangaroa M\u0101ori towed the ''Boyd'' towards their village until it grounded on mudflats near Motu Wai (Red Island). They spent several days ransacking the ship, tossing flour, salt pork, and bottled wine overboard. The M\u0101ori were interested in a large cache of muskets and gunpowder.\n\nAbout 20 M\u0101ori smashed barrels of gunpowder and attempted to make the muskets functional. Chief Piopio sparked a flint. This ignited the gunpowder, causing a massive explosion that killed him and nine other M\u0101ori instantly. A fire then swept the ship igniting its cargo of whale oil. Soon all that was left of the ''Boyd'' was a burnt-out sunken hull. M\u0101ori declared the hull [[Tapu (Polynesian culture)|tapu]], sacred or prohibited.\n\n==Rescue==\n\nWhen news of the massacre reached European settlements, Captain [[Alexander Berry]] undertook a rescue mission aboard ''The City of Edinburgh.'' Berry rescued the four survivors: Ann Morley and her baby, Thomas Davis (or Davison), and Betsy Broughton.\n\nThe ''City of Edinburgh'' crew found piles of human bones on the shoreline, with many evincing cannibalism.<ref name=\"McNab10\">McNab quotes Captain Berry saying, \"We had seen the mangled fragments and fresh bones of our countrymen, with the marks even of the teeth remaining on them\". [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d10.html Chapter 10: The Massacre of the Boyd, 1809 and 1810], in ''From Tasman To Marsden: A History of Northern New Zealand from 1642 to 1818'', by Robert McNab. Published by J. Wilkie & Company, Dunedin, 1914.</ref>\n\nCaptain Berry captured two M\u0101ori chiefs responsible for the massacre, at first holding them for ransom for the return of survivors. After the survivors were returned, Berry told the chiefs that they would be taken to Europe to answer for their crimes unless they released the ''Boyd's'' papers.<ref name=NZETC>[http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d11.html New Zealand Electronic Text Centre - From Tasman to Marsden: Chapter XI - After the Massacre 1810 to 1814]</ref>  After the papers were given to him, he released the chiefs. He made it a condition of their release that they would be \"degraded from their rank, and received among the number of his slaves\", although he never expected this condition to be complied with.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last        = Berry\n | first       = Alexander\n |date=April 1819\n | journal     = The Edinburgh Magazine\n | title       = Particulars of a late visit to New Zealand, and of the measures taken for rescuing some of English captives there\n | pages       = 304\n | url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=UlwAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA304\n}}</ref>\nThey expressed gratitude for the mercy. Berry's gesture avoided further bloodshed, an inevitability had the chiefs been executed.\n\nThe four people rescued were taken on board Berry's ship bound for the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. However, the ship encountered storms and was damaged, and after repairs arrived in [[Lima, Peru]].  Mrs Morley died while in Lima.<ref>\n{{cite news\n  | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419\n  | date = 8 May 1832\n  | newspaper = The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser \n  | page = 4 \n  | title = The Boyd\n}}\n</ref>\nThe boy, called Davis or Davison, went from Lima to [[England]] aboard the ''Archduke Charles'', and later worked for Berry in [[New South Wales]]. He drowned while exploring the entrance to the [[Shoalhaven River]] with Berry in 1822.<ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Swords\n  | first = Meg\n  | isbn = 0-85587-128-8\n  | title = Alexander Berry and Elizabeth Wollstonecraft\n  | page = 9\n| year = 1978\n }}\n</ref>\nMrs Morley's child and Betsy Broughton were taken onwards by Berry to [[Rio de Janeiro]], from where they returned to [[Sydney]] in May 1812 aboard the ''Atalanta''.<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article628475 |title=Ship News. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser|The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)]] |location=NSW |date=23 May 1812 |accessdate=8 January 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nBetsy Broughton married Charles Throsby, nephew of the explorer [[Charles Throsby]], and died in 1891.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.pic-an23478163\n  | title = Betsy Broughton (A Brief Biography)\n  | publisher = National Library of Australia\n  | accessdate = 29 October 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A toddler's survival story |url=https://www.nla.gov.au/blogs/treasures/2015/11/09/a-toddlers-survival-story |website=National Library of Australia |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn March 1810, sailors from five whaling ships launched a revenge attack. Their target was the Motu Apo pa at [[Rangihoua Bay]] belonging to [[Te Pahi]], the chief who tried to rescue the ''Boyd'' survivors and then saw them killed. Te Pahi had later accepted one of the ''Boyd's'' small boats and some other booty, and his name was confused with that of Te Puhi, who was one of the plotters of the massacre. This was the belief of [[Samuel Marsden]], the prominent early missionary who said it was Te Ara (George) and his brother Te Puhi who took the Boyd as revenge.<ref name=Ballara>{{cite web|last1=Ballara|first1=Angela|title=Te Pahi|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t53/te-pahi|website=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CARv1\">{{cite book |last1= Carleton |first1=Hugh |authorlink1= |title= The Life of Henry Williams|format= |accessdate=  |year= 1874 |publisher= [[Early New Zealand Books]] (ENZB), University of Auckland Library|location= |language= |isbn= |oclc=  |doi= |id= |pages=25\u201326|chapter= Vol. I |chapterurl=http://www.enzb.auckland.ac.nz/document?wid=1038&action=null|quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref> In the attack between 16 and 60 M\u0101ori and one sailor were killed.<ref name=\"trove.nla.gov.au\"/> \n\nTe Pahi, who was wounded in the neck and chest, realised that the sailors had attacked him because of the actions of the Whangaroa Maori. He gathered his remaining warriors and attacked Whangaroa, where he was killed by a spear thrust some time before 28 April.<ref name=NZETC/>\n\nNews of the Boyd Massacre reached Australia and Europe, delaying a planned visit of missionaries until 1814.<ref>[http://www.waitangi.com/ww/chap01.html www.waitangi.com - Christianity among the New Zealanders: Chapter 1 - 1808 to 1814]</ref> A notice was printed and circulated in Europe advising against visiting \"that cursed shore\" of New Zealand, at the risk of being eaten by cannibals.<ref>[http://google.com/search?q=cache:0Nwi5GLa65gJ:www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident+whangaroa+cursed+boyd+shores&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=1&client=firefox-a New Zealand History Online: The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?]</ref>\n\nShipping to New Zealand \"fell away to almost nothing\" during the next three years.<ref name=NZETC/>\n\n==Cultural references==\n\nDetails of the massacre have featured in numerous non-fiction publications. One of the most comprehensive was:\n* ''The Burning of the 'Boyd' - A Saga of Culture Clash'' (1984), [[Wade Doak]]\n\nThe massacre was the subject of a 2010 New Zealand [[children's book]]:\n* ''The Shadow of the Boyd'', by Diana Menefy\n\nHistorical fiction references include:\n* ''The Boyd Massacre: The true and terrible story of'', (2005), {{ISBN|978-0646447957}}, Ian Macdonald (a descendant of Boyd survivor Betsey Broughton)\n* ''Burning the Evidence'' by Terri Kessell, {{ISBN|978-1877340147}}, follows Ann Morley, who lived with Maori for some months before her rescue by Alexander Berry \n\nThe massacre has also featured in several paintings:\n* {{ill|Louis Auguste Sainson|de}}, ''The Boyd Incident'', (1839)\n* [[Louis John Steele]], ''The Blowing Up of the Boyd'', (1889)\n* Walter Wright,  ''The Burning of the Boyd'', (1908)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of massacres in New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110609212225/http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html A comprehensive report by Tony Flude]\n*[http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/1966/B/boydMassacreOf/en \"BOYD\", MASSACRE OF], from ''An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand'', edited by A. H. McLintock, 1966. Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand, updated 18 September 2007.\n*[http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d10.html The Massacre of the Boyd, 1809 and 1810] and [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d11.html After the Massacre, 1810 to 1814], Chapters 10 and 11 in ''From Tasman To Marsden: A History of Northern New Zealand from 1642 to 1818'', by Robert McNab. Published by J. Wilkie & Company, Dunedin, 1914.\n*Massacre of the Boyd, in [http://www.waitangi.com/ww/chap01.html Chapter 1], in ''Christianity Among The New Zealanders'', by the Right Rev. William Williams, D.C.L., Bishop of Waiapu. Seeley, Jackson, and Halliday, London, 1867.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/media/photo/boyd-incident-painting Depiction of the capture of the ''Boyd'' in Whangaroa Harbour], Louis Auguste Sainson, 1840s?.\n*[http://www.teara.govt.nz/EarthSeaAndSky/SeaAndAirTransport/Shipwrecks/2/ENZ-Resources/Standard/4/en ''The Burning of the'' Boyd], oil painting by Walter Wright, 1908.\n\n{{1809 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{coord missing|New Zealand}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Boyd'' massacre}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1809]]\n[[Category:Cannibalism in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Massacres in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1809 in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Far North District]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:History of the Northland Region]]\n[[Category:December 1809 events]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1809]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Louis John Steel - The blowing up of the Boyd Steele (1889).jpg|thumb|right|300px|''The Blowing Up of the Boyd'' by [[Louis John Steele]], 1889]]\nThe '''''Boyd'' massacre''' occurred in December 1809 when [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] residents of [[Whangaroa Harbour]] in northern [[New Zealand]] killed and ate between 66 and 70 Europeans.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419 , ''The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser, 8 May 1832, retrieved 4 July 2011]</ref> This is reputedly the highest number of Europeans killed by M\u0101ori in a single event in New Zealand, and the incident is also one of the bloodiest instances of [[cannibalism]] on record. The massacre is thought to have been in revenge for the whipping of a young M\u0101ori chief<ref name=\"nzhistory.net.nz\">[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident New Zealand History Online, ''The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?'' Retrieved 3 May 2011]</ref> by the crew of the sailing ship ''[[Boyd (1783 ship)|Boyd]]''.\n\nIn retribution, European whalers attacked the island [[P\u0101 (M\u0101ori)|pa]] of chief [[Te Pahi]] about 60&nbsp;km south-east<!--bearing from boyd site to te pahi island is 115 deg-->,<ref name=\"teara.govt.nz\">[http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t53/1?setlang=en The Encyclopedia Of New Zealand, ''Dictionary of New Zealand Biography'', TePahi, retrieved 21 May 2011]</ref><ref name=\"nzhistory.net.nz\"/> in the mistaken belief that he ordered the killings. Between 16 and 60 Maori and one European died in the clash.<ref name=\"teara.govt.nz\"/><ref name=\"trove.nla.gov.au\">http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page6631?zoomLevel=2</ref> News of the events delayed the first missionary visits to the country, and caused the number of shipping visits to fall to \"almost nothing\" over the next few years.\n\n==Background==\nThe ''[[Boyd (1783 ship)|Boyd]]'' was a 395-ton ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]]) [[brigantine]] [[convict ship]] that sailed in October 1809 from Australia's [[Sydney Cove]] to [[Whangaroa]] on the east coast of New Zealand's [[Northland Peninsula]] to pick up [[kauri]] [[Spar (sailing)|spar]]s. She was under the command of Captain [[John Thompson (ship captain)|John Thompson]] and carried about 70 people.\n\nThe ship carried several passengers, including ex-convicts who had completed their transportation sentences and four or five New Zealanders who were returning to their homeland. Among the latter was Te Ara, or Tarrah, known to the crew as George, the son of a [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] [[Tribal chief|chief]] from Whangaroa. Te Ara had spent more than a year on board different vessels that included a sealing expedition to islands in the [[Southern Ocean]].\n\nOn the ''Boyd'' he was expected to work his passage on the ship. Some accounts state that he declined to do so because he was ill or because of his status as a chief's son.<ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\">{{Cite web |url=http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2003-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609212225/http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html |archive-date=2011-06-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Shipwrecks and Disasters at Sea W.H.G. Kingston. George Routledge and Sons, London. 1873</ref> Another account states that the ship's cook accidentally threw some [[pewter]] spoons overboard and accused Te Ara of stealing them to avoid being flogged himself.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419 The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser, May 1832, page 4]</ref> [[Alexander Berry]], in a letter describing the events, said: \"The captain had been rather too hasty in resenting some slight theft.\"<ref>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/11933/11933-h/11933-h.htm#CHAPTER_XI A NARRATIVE OF A NINE MONTHS' RESIDENCE IN NEW ZEALAND CHAPTER XI]</ref>\n\nWhatever the reason, the result was that the captain deprived him of food and had him tied to a [[capstan (nautical)|capstan]] and whipped.<ref name=\"homepages.ihug.co.nz\"/>\n\nThis treatment of Te Ara prompted him to seek ''[[utu (M\u0101ori concept)|utu]]'', or revenge. Te Ara regained the confidence of the captain and persuaded him to put into Whangaroa Bay, assuring him that it was the best place to secure the timber he desired.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUpon reaching Whangaroa, Te Ara reported his indignities to his tribe and displayed the whip marks on his back. In accordance with M\u0101ori customs, they formed a plan for ''utu''. Under British law, whipping was the common punishment for minor crimes. A British person could be legally hanged for stealing goods to the value of 5 shillings. In M\u0101ori culture the son of a chief was a privileged figure who did not bow to an outsider's authority. Physical punishment of his son caused the chief to suffer a loss of face (or \"[[mana]]\"), and to M\u0101ori this warranted a violent retribution.\n\n==Killings==\nThree days after the ''Boyd's'' arrival, the M\u0101ori invited Captain Thompson to follow their canoes to find suitable kauri trees. Thompson, his chief officer and three others followed the canoes to the entrance of the [[Kaeo River]]. The remaining crew stayed aboard with the passengers, preparing the vessel for the voyage to England.\n\nWhen the boats were beyond the ''Boyd's'' sight the M\u0101ori attacked the [[p\u0101keh\u0101]] (foreigners), killing them all with clubs and axes. The M\u0101ori stripped the western clothes from the victims and a group donned them as disguise. Another group carried the bodies to their [[p\u0101 (M\u0101ori)|p\u0101]] (village) to be eaten.<ref name=\"NZHistory\">[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?], New Zealand History Online, Ministry for Culture and Heritage. Updated 2008-01-24. Accessed 2008-05-05.</ref>\n\nAt dusk the disguised group manned the longboat, and at nightfall they slipped alongside the ''Boyd'' and were greeted by the crew. Other M\u0101ori canoes awaited the signal to attack. The first to die was a ship's officer: the attackers then crept around the deck, stealthily killing all the crew. The passengers were called to the deck and then killed. Five people hid up the mast among the rigging, where they witnessed the dismembering of their friends and colleagues' bodies below.\n\nThe next morning the survivors saw a large canoe carrying chief [[Te Pahi]] from the Bay of Islands enter the harbour. The chief had come to the area to trade with the Whangaroa M\u0101ori. The Europeans called out to Te Pahi's canoe for help. After Te Pahi had gathered the survivors from the ''Boyd'', they headed for shore. But two Whangaroa canoes pursued them. As the survivors fled along the beach, Te Pahi watched as all but one were caught and killed by the pursuers.\n\n==European survivors==\n\nFive people were spared in the [[massacre]]: Ann Morley and her baby, in a cabin; apprentice Thomas Davis (or Davison), hidden in the hold; the second mate; and two-year-old Betsy Broughton, taken by a local chief who put a feather in her hair and kept her for three weeks before rescue. The second mate was killed and eaten when his usefulness in making fish-hooks was exhausted.<ref name=\"NZHistory\"/>\n\n==Destruction of the ''Boyd''==\nThe Whangaroa M\u0101ori towed the ''Boyd'' towards their village until it grounded on mudflats near Motu Wai (Red Island). They spent several days ransacking the ship, tossing flour, salt pork, and bottled wine overboard. The M\u0101ori were interested in a large cache of muskets and gunpowder.\n\nAbout 20 M\u0101ori smashed barrels of gunpowder and attempted to make the muskets functional. Chief Piopio sparked a flint. This ignited the gunpowder, causing a massive explosion that killed him and nine other M\u0101ori instantly. A fire then swept the ship igniting its cargo of whale oil. Soon all that was left of the ''Boyd'' was a burnt-out sunken hull. M\u0101ori declared the hull [[Tapu (Polynesian culture)|tapu]], sacred or prohibited.\n\n==Rescue==\n\nWhen news of the massacre reached European settlements, Captain [[Alexander Berry]] undertook a rescue mission aboard ''The City of Edinburgh.'' Berry rescued the four survivors: Ann Morley and her baby, Thomas Davis (or Davison), and Betsy Broughton.\n\nThe ''City of Edinburgh'' crew found piles of human bones on the shoreline, with many evincing cannibalism.<ref name=\"McNab10\">McNab quotes Captain Berry saying, \"We had seen the mangled fragments and fresh bones of our countrymen, with the marks even of the teeth remaining on them\". [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d10.html Chapter 10: The Massacre of the Boyd, 1809 and 1810], in ''From Tasman To Marsden: A History of Northern New Zealand from 1642 to 1818'', by Robert McNab. Published by J. Wilkie & Company, Dunedin, 1914.</ref>\n\nCaptain Berry captured two M\u0101ori chiefs responsible for the massacre, at first holding them for ransom for the return of survivors. After the survivors were returned, Berry told the chiefs that they would be taken to Europe to answer for their crimes unless they released the ''Boyd's'' papers.<ref name=NZETC>[http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d11.html New Zealand Electronic Text Centre - From Tasman to Marsden: Chapter XI - After the Massacre 1810 to 1814]</ref>  After the papers were given to him, he released the chiefs. He made it a condition of their release that they would be \"degraded from their rank, and received among the number of his slaves\", although he never expected this condition to be complied with.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last        = Berry\n | first       = Alexander\n |date=April 1819\n | journal     = The Edinburgh Magazine\n | title       = Particulars of a late visit to New Zealand, and of the measures taken for rescuing some of English captives there\n | pages       = 304\n | url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=UlwAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA304\n}}</ref>\nThey expressed gratitude for the mercy. Berry's gesture avoided further bloodshed, an inevitability had the chiefs been executed.\n\nThe four people rescued were taken on board Berry's ship bound for the [[Cape of Good Hope]]. However, the ship encountered storms and was damaged, and after repairs arrived in [[Lima, Peru]].  Mrs Morley died while in Lima.<ref>\n{{cite news\n  | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2206419\n  | date = 8 May 1832\n  | newspaper = The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser \n  | page = 4 \n  | title = The Boyd\n}}\n</ref>\nThe boy, called Davis or Davison, went from Lima to [[England]] aboard the ''Archduke Charles'', and later worked for Berry in [[New South Wales]]. He drowned while exploring the entrance to the [[Shoalhaven River]] with Berry in 1822.<ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Swords\n  | first = Meg\n  | isbn = 0-85587-128-8\n  | title = Alexander Berry and Elizabeth Wollstonecraft\n  | page = 9\n| year = 1978\n }}\n</ref>\nMrs Morley's child and Betsy Broughton were taken onwards by Berry to [[Rio de Janeiro]], from where they returned to [[Sydney]] in May 1812 aboard the ''Atalanta''.<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article628475 |title=Ship News. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser|The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)]] |location=NSW |date=23 May 1812 |accessdate=8 January 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\nBetsy Broughton married Charles Throsby, nephew of the explorer [[Charles Throsby]], and died in 1891.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.pic-an23478163\n  | title = Betsy Broughton (A Brief Biography)\n  | publisher = National Library of Australia\n  | accessdate = 29 October 2009\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=A toddler's survival story |url=https://www.nla.gov.au/blogs/treasures/2015/11/09/a-toddlers-survival-story |website=National Library of Australia |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nIn March 1810, sailors from five whaling ships launched a revenge attack. Their target was the Motu Apo pa at [[Rangihoua Bay]] belonging to [[Te Pahi]], the chief who tried to rescue the ''Boyd'' survivors and then saw them killed. Te Pahi had later accepted one of the ''Boyd's'' small boats and some other booty, and his name was confused with that of Te Puhi, who was one of the plotters of the massacre. This was the belief of [[Samuel Marsden]], the prominent early missionary who said it was Te Ara (George) and his brother Te Puhi who took the Boyd as revenge.<ref name=Ballara>{{cite web|last1=Ballara|first1=Angela|title=Te Pahi|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/biographies/1t53/te-pahi|website=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CARv1\">{{cite book |last1= Carleton |first1=Hugh |authorlink1= |title= The Life of Henry Williams|format= |accessdate=  |year= 1874 |publisher= [[Early New Zealand Books]] (ENZB), University of Auckland Library|location= |language= |isbn= |oclc=  |doi= |id= |pages=25\u201326|chapter= Vol. I |chapterurl=http://www.enzb.auckland.ac.nz/document?wid=1038&action=null|quote= |ref= |bibcode= }}</ref> In the attack between 16 and 60 M\u0101ori and one sailor were killed.<ref name=\"trove.nla.gov.au\"/> \n\nTe Pahi, who was wounded in the neck and chest, realised that the sailors had attacked him because of the actions of the Whangaroa Maori. He gathered his remaining warriors and attacked Whangaroa, where he was killed by a spear thrust some time before 28 April.<ref name=NZETC/>\n\nNews of the Boyd Massacre reached Australia and Europe, delaying a planned visit of missionaries until 1814.<ref>[http://www.waitangi.com/ww/chap01.html www.waitangi.com - Christianity among the New Zealanders: Chapter 1 - 1808 to 1814]</ref> A notice was printed and circulated in Europe advising against visiting \"that cursed shore\" of New Zealand, at the risk of being eaten by cannibals.<ref>[http://google.com/search?q=cache:0Nwi5GLa65gJ:www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/maori-european-contact-before-1840/the-boyd-incident+whangaroa+cursed+boyd+shores&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=1&client=firefox-a New Zealand History Online: The Boyd incident - a frontier of chaos?]</ref>\n\nShipping to New Zealand \"fell away to almost nothing\" during the next three years.<ref name=NZETC/>\n\n==Cultural references==\n\nDetails of the massacre have featured in numerous non-fiction publications. One of the most comprehensive was:\n* ''The Burning of the 'Boyd' - A Saga of Culture Clash'' (1984), [[Wade Doak]]\n\nThe massacre was the subject of a 2010 New Zealand [[children's book]]:\n* ''The Shadow of the Boyd'', by Diana Menefy\n\nHistorical fiction references include:\n* ''The Boyd Massacre: The true and terrible story of'', (2005), {{ISBN|978-0646447957}}, Ian Macdonald (a descendant of Boyd survivor Betsey Broughton)\n* ''Burning the Evidence'' by Terri Kessell, {{ISBN|978-1877340147}}, follows Ann Morley, who lived with Maori for some months before her rescue by Alexander Berry \n\nThe massacre has also featured in several paintings:\n* {{ill|Louis Auguste Sainson|de}}, ''The Boyd Incident'', (1839)\n* [[Louis John Steele]], ''The Blowing Up of the Boyd'', (1889)\n* Walter Wright,  ''The Burning of the Boyd'', (1908)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of massacres in New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110609212225/http://homepages.ihug.co.nz/~tonyf/loot/boyd.html A comprehensive report by Tony Flude]\n*[http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/1966/B/boydMassacreOf/en \"BOYD\", MASSACRE OF], from ''An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand'', edited by A. H. McLintock, 1966. Te Ara - The Encyclopedia of New Zealand, updated 18 September 2007.\n*[http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d10.html The Massacre of the Boyd, 1809 and 1810] and [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-McNTasm-t1-body-d11.html After the Massacre, 1810 to 1814], Chapters 10 and 11 in ''From Tasman To Marsden: A History of Northern New Zealand from 1642 to 1818'', by Robert McNab. Published by J. Wilkie & Company, Dunedin, 1914.\n*Massacre of the Boyd, in [http://www.waitangi.com/ww/chap01.html Chapter 1], in ''Christianity Among The New Zealanders'', by the Right Rev. William Williams, D.C.L., Bishop of Waiapu. Seeley, Jackson, and Halliday, London, 1867.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/media/photo/boyd-incident-painting Depiction of the capture of the ''Boyd'' in Whangaroa Harbour], Louis Auguste Sainson, 1840s?.\n*[http://www.teara.govt.nz/EarthSeaAndSky/SeaAndAirTransport/Shipwrecks/2/ENZ-Resources/Standard/4/en ''The Burning of the'' Boyd], oil painting by Walter Wright, 1908.\n\n{{1809 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{coord missing|New Zealand}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Boyd'' massacre}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1809]]\n[[Category:Cannibalism in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Massacres in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1809 in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Far North District]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:History of the Northland Region]]\n[[Category:December 1809 events]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1809]]\n", "name_user": "Lewis, of Campbell", "label": "safe", "comment": "Made it sound a bit better", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boyd_massacre"}
{"title_page": "Betty Crocker", "text_new": "[[File:Betty Crocker official logo.svg|thumb|Betty Crocker logo]]\n[[File:ProdPack-Betty-Crocker-Brownies-Small.jpg|right|thumb|A box of Fudge Brownie mix]]\n\n'''Betty Crocker''' is a brand and fictional character used in advertising campaigns for food and recipes.  It was originally created by the [[General Mills|Washburn-Crosby Company]] in 1921 following a contest in the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]''.  In 1954, [[General Mills]], [[Fortune 500|an American Fortune 500 corporation,]] branded the red spoon logo, giving various food-related merchandise the Betty Seal of Approval.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goetz|first1=Kathryn|title=Betty Crocker|url=http://www.mnopedia.org/person/betty-crocker|publisher=MNOPEDIA|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> A portrait of Betty Crocker, first commissioned in 1936 and revised several times since, appears on printed advertisements and product packaging. On television and radio broadcasts, Betty Crocker was portrayed by several actresses, on radio by [[Marjorie Husted]] for twenty years, and on television by [[Adelaide Hawley Cumming]] between 1949 and 1964.\n\nThe character was developed in 1920 as a way to give a personalized response to consumer product questions. The name Betty was selected because it was viewed as a cheery, all-American name.  It was paired with the last name Crocker, in honor of William Crocker, a Washburn Crosby Company director.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Story of Betty Crocker|url=http://www.bettycrocker.com/menus-holidays-parties/mhplibrary/parties-and-get-togethers/vintage-betty/the-story-of-betty-crocker|website=Betty Crocker|publisher=Betty Crocker|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDescribed as an American [[cultural icon]], the image of Betty Crocker has endured several generations, adapting to changing social, political and economic currents.<ref name=\"Adema\">{{cite book|last=Adema |first=Pauline|editor1=Dennis Hall|editor2=Susan G. Hall|title=American Icons: An Encyclopedia of the People, Places, and Things that Have Shaped Our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlxHgYqgDswC&pg=PA73|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-02767-3|pages=73\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{citation | last = Patrick | first = Jeanette | title = Aunt Jemima and Betty Crocker: American Cultural Icons that Never Existed | publisher = [[National Women's History Museum]] | year = 2017 | url = https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/aunt-jemimar-and-betty-crocker}}</ref> Apart from advertising campaigns in printed, broadcast and digital media, she received a number of cultural references in film, literature, music and comics; most notably in the webcomic, [[Homestuck]], as one of the main antagonists. \n\n==Creation==\nBetty Crocker was created in 1921 by [[General Mills|Washburn-Crosby]] and advertiser [[Bruce Fairchild Barton|Bruce Barton]].<ref name=\"Lippy2005\">{{cite book|author=Charles H. Lippy|title=Do Real Men Pray?: Images of the Christian Man and Male Spirituality in White Protestant America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hA85UeTuGzQC&pg=PA133|year=2005|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press|isbn=978-1-57233-358-1|pages=133\u2013}}</ref> Under [[Marjorie Husted]]'s supervision, the image of Betty Crocker became the \"Zeus\" of General Mills. In 1921, Washburn Crosby merged with other milling companies to form General Mills.<ref name=\"Adema\"/>\n\nIn 1924, Crocker acquired a voice with the debut of \"The Betty Crocker Cooking School of the Air\" on one station in Minneapolis. It was the country's first radio cooking program. Blanche Ingersoll followed by Husted were selected to portray Betty Crocker. The show proved popular, and eventually was carried nationally on NBC Radio, with Agnes White as Betty. Over the next three decades, the women would anonymously portray Betty Crocker on the air and at cooking schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vchistory.org/people/agnes-white-tizard-betty-crocker/|title=Agnes White Tizard: Betty Crocker|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, Betty Crocker [[coupon]]s were introduced. Inserted in bags of flour, they could be used to reduce the cost of [[Oneida Limited]] [[cutlery|flatware]]. By 1932, this scheme had become so popular that General Mills began to offer an entire set of flatware; the pattern was called \"Friendship\" (later renamed \"Medality\"). In 1937, the coupons were printed on the outside of packages, copy on which told purchasers to \"save and redeem for huge savings on fine kitchen and home accessories in our [[mail-order catalog|catalog]]\".\n\n==Cookbook publications ==\nFrom 1930, General Mills issued softbound recipe books, including in 1933 ''Betty Crocker's 101 Delicious [[Bisquick]] Creations, As Made and Served by Well-Known Gracious Hostesses, Famous Chefs, Distinguished Epicures and Smart Luminaries of Movieland.''{{citation needed|date = January 2012}}\n\n1941\u20131945: The ''Betty Crocker Cook Book of All-Purpose Baking'' was published as an aid to wartime considerations in cooking.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvits|first=Janet|title=Betty Crocker Edition History|url=http://www.cookbookjj.com/college/betty_crocker.htm|publisher=General Mills}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, the ''Betty Crocker Picture Cookbook'' was published. It was written by nutritionist Agnes White Tizard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alphadeltapi.org/contentmanager/page.asp?webpageid=622|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905164818/http://www.alphadeltapi.org/contentmanager/page.asp?webpageid=622|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 September 2010|title=Accomplished Alpha Delta Pi Members in Education and Science|accessdate=26 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the 10th edition of the Betty Crocker cookbook was published, as well as a [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[English language|English]] bilingual book that collects some of the more common recipes for Spanish-speaking readers looking to cook American-style food. An 11th edition, in ring-binder format, appeared in 2011. At least 17 other Betty Crocker recipe collections were also in print in 2015. Recipes and collections are also available digitally.<ref>{{cite book|last1=man|first1=VANNY|title=the crokk|publisher=Hannibal}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n''Betty Crocker'' programs first appeared on radio on local stations in 1924. The first network ''Betty Crocker'' broadcast was on [[NBC]] in 1926. The show remained on network radio until 1953; most of the time the program was on NBC or [[CBS]], but it was on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from 1947 to 1953.<ref name=\"dunningota\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration |quote=Betty Crocker, cooking advice. |last1=Dunning |first1=John| title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio| date=1998| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=New York, NY| isbn=978-0-19-507678-3| page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/82 82]| edition=Revised| accessdate=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1949, the actress [[Adelaide Hawley Cumming]] became Betty Crocker for many years. She appeared for several years on ''[[The George Burns and Gracie Allen Show]]'',<ref name=\"cbsmarks\"/> and even had her own TV show, ''[[Betty Crocker Star Matinee]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McDonough|first1=John|last2=Egolf|first2=Karen|title=The Advertising Age Encyclopedia of Advertising|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135949136|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QpLtCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1280&dq=%22Betty+Crocker+Star+Matinee%22#v=onepage&q=%22Betty%20Crocker%20Star%20Matinee%22&f=false|accessdate=17 October 2017|language=en}}</ref> She also appeared in the [[CBS]] network's first color commercial, in which she baked a \"mystery fruit cake\". Hawley continued to portray Betty Crocker until 1964.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adelaide Hawley Cumming, 93, Television's First Betty Crocker|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/25/arts/adelaide-hawley-cumming-93-television-s-first-betty-crocker.html|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nA portrait of Betty Crocker was first commissioned in 1936,<ref name=drsfsc>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QdwRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Tu8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6657%2C5142832 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=New Betty Crocker dressed for success |date=May 23, 1986 |page=17 }}</ref> a \"motherly image\" that \"blended the features of several Home Service Department members\" that was painted by [[Neysa McMein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saic.edu/150/bold-suffragette-betty-crocker|title=From Bold Suffragette to Betty Crocker - 150 Years of SAIC|author=|date=|website=www.saic.edu|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> It subtly changed over the years, but always accommodated General Mills' cultural perception of the American homemaker&nbsp;\u2014 knowledgeable and caring.<ref name=drsfsc/> The 1996 portrait of Betty Crocker, according to General Mills, was partially inspired by a \"computerized composite\" of \"75 women of diverse backgrounds and ages.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Betty Crocker Portraits|url=http://www.bettycrocker.com/tips/aboutthekitchens/portraits|publisher=General Mills|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref>  These portraits were always painted, with no real person ever having posed as a model.{{citation needed|date = January 2012}}\n\nIn 1945, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine named Betty Crocker the second most popular woman in America; [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] was named first.<ref name=\"marks\">{{cite book |isbn=0743265017 |oclc=56880048 |lccn=2004061566 |last=Marks |first=Susan |title=Finding Betty Crocker : the secret life of America's first lady of food |date=2005 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |url=https://archive.org/details/findingbettycroc00mark }}</ref> ''Fortune'' published an article \"outing\" Betty Crocker's fictitious nature, calling her a \"fake\" and a \"fraud.\"{{specify|reason=Was Betty Crocker's outing in the same 1945 Fortune article as the one in which they named Betty Crocker the 2nd most popular woman? CBS source is vague, need to check the details in Marks's book or Fortune's archives.|date=July 2016}}<ref name=\"cbsmarks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/betty-crocker-unveiled/ |title=Betty Crocker Unveiled |last=Dakss|first=Brian |date=May 6, 2005 |newspaper=[[CBS]] |department=[[CBS News Sunday Morning]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural References==\n\nIn the multimedia webcomic Homestuck, Betty Crocker is a shady and conspiratorial company owned by who is later revealed to be one of the main antagonists of the story. Like with many other pop-culture references in Homestuck, the brand's cake mix and fruit gushers are initially a running gag. However, as the story grows more complex, so too does Betty Crocker's seemingly insignificant presence, wherein the company's true identity is revealed to be a multiversal, subjugating entity. \n\n==Legacy==\nThe [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]] suburb of [[Golden Valley, Minnesota]] (where General Mills is headquartered) has a street named Betty Crocker Drive.<ref>{{cite web|title=City Streets, Sidewalks, & Trails Map|url=http://www.goldenvalleymn.gov/streets/pdf/streets-trails-walks-map.pdf|website=City of Golden Valley Minnesota|publisher=City of Golden Valley, Minnesota|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of Betty Crocker-branded products, such as plastic food containers and measuring cups, and a line of small appliances like popcorn poppers and sandwich makers with the Betty Crocker brand name.\n\nIn 2006, the Betty Crocker catalog operation went out of business with all of its inventory on sale. Points were redeemable until December 15, 2006. A new online store was launched in April 2007 but discontinued sometime thereafter.\n\nBetty Crocker recipes and tips from the \"Atomic Age\" of the 1950s are of cultural interest.<ref name=NYTM102715>{{cite news|author1=Tamar Adler|title=Betty Crocker's Absurd, Gorgeous Atomic-Age Creations The iconic brand's midcentury recipes evoke the era's peculiar optimism, encased in gelatin and smothered in mayonnaise.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/magazine/betty-crockers-absurd-gorgeous-atomic-age-creations.html|accessdate=November 1, 2015|work=The New York Times Magazine|date=October 27, 2015|quote=segment of American culinary life is on display}}</ref><ref name=BoxOfBetty>{{cite web|title=A Box of Betty|url=http://aboxofbetty.tumblr.com/archive|website=aboxofbetty.tumblr.com|publisher=Tumbir|accessdate=November 1, 2015|format=Images}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n* Bac-Os\n* Betty Crocker Brownie bar\n* [[Betty Crocker Cookbook]]\n* Betty Crocker [[baking mix]]es\n* [[Fruit Roll-Ups]]\n* Betty Crocker canned frosting\n* Bowl Appetit shelf-stable entrees\n* Betty Crocker Soda Licious (discontinued)\n* Cake and dessert decorating products\n* [[Dunkaroos|Dunk-a-roos]]\n* [[Fruit by the Foot]]\n* Fruit Gushers<ref name=\"product catalogue\">[http://www.generalmills.com/Home/Brands/Baking_Products/Betty_Crocker/Brand%20Product%20List%20Page.aspx Betty Crocker product list], General Mills</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bettycrocker.com/products|title=Products|author=|date=|website=bettycrocker.com|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Hamburger Helper]] and related products\n* Potato Buds instant [[mashed potatoes]]\n* Suddenly Salad mixes\n* \"Shake and make\" pancake mix\n* Warm Delights microwavable desserts\n* Imperial Drones\n* Fascist Dictators (jane u know what you did)\n==See also==\n* [[Betty Crocker Kitchens]]\n* [[Betty Bossi]]\n* [https://mspaintadventures.fandom.com/wiki/The_Condesce The Condesce]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite web |title=Who Was Betty Crocker?|author=Tori Avey |url=https://www.pbs.org/food/the-history-kitchen/who-was-betty-crocker/ |date=February 15, 2013 |publisher=[[PBS]] Food |accessdate=}}\n* Dunning, John. ''On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio.''  Oxford University Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-19-507678-8}}\n* Marks, Susan. (2007) ''Finding Betty Crocker: The Secret Life of America's First Lady of Food'' University of Minnesota Press. {{ISBN|978-0-8166-5018-7}} (popular book.)\n* Crocker, Betty. ''Betty Crocker's Picture Cook Book''. New York: McGraw\u2013Hill and General Mills, 1950 (first edition of the \"Big Red\" cookbook.)\n* Gray, James. ''Business without Boundary: The Story of General Mills''. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 1954 (scholarly history of General Mills, including the invention of Crocker.)\n* Shapiro, Laura. \"Is She Real?\" In ''Something from the Oven: Reinventing Dinner in 1950s America'', 169\u2013209. New York: Viking, 2004 (chapter on Betty Crocker in a popular book with footnotes.)\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190422052226/http://gogd.tjs-labs.com/gallery-view?keyword=betty*crocker Collection of mid-twentieth century advertising featuring Betty Crocker] from The TJS Labs Gallery of Graphic Design.\n* [http://www.mnopedia.org/person/betty-crocker Betty Crocker in MNopedia, the Minnesota Encyclopedia] \n* [http://www.bettycrocker.com/ www.bettycrocker.com]\u2014Betty Crocker official site\n* [http://www.bettycrocker.com/products www.bettycrocker.com/products]\u2014Betty Crocker products\n* {{Citation | url = http://chnm.gmu.edu/sidelights/who-was-betty-crocker/ | title = Who was Betty Crocker | publisher = GMU | access-date = 2011-01-06 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110628175931/http://chnm.gmu.edu/sidelights/who-was-betty-crocker/ | archive-date = 2011-06-28 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{Citation| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080308040953/http://www.findingbettycrocker.com/ | archivedate = 2008-03-08 | url = http://www.findingbettycrocker.com/ | title = Finding Betty Crocker | first = Susan | last = Marks |url-status=dead}}\n* {{Citation| url = http://www.ilovethefingerlakes.com/history/famous-people-cumming.htm | title = Biography | first = Adelaide | last = Fish Hawley Cumming | publisher = I love the Fingerlakes}}.\n\n{{General Mills}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Advertising characters|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Mascots introduced in 1921|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Radio characters introduced in 1924|Crocker]]\n[[Category:Female characters in radio|Crocker]]\n[[Category:Cookbooks|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Corporate mascots|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Minnesota|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Food advertising characters|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:General Mills brands]]\n[[Category:General Mills characters|Crocker, Betty]]\n[[Category:Baking mixes]]\n[[Category:Food product brands]]\n[[Category:Media franchises introduced in 1921]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Betty Crocker official logo.svg|thumb|Betty Crocker logo]]\n[[File:ProdPack-Betty-Crocker-Brownies-Small.jpg|right|thumb|A box of Fudge Brownie mix]]\n\n'''Betty Crocker''' is a brand and fictional character used in advertising campaigns for food and recipes.  It was originally created by the [[General Mills|Washburn-Crosby Company]] in 1921 following a contest in the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]''.  In 1954, [[General Mills]], [[Fortune 500|an American Fortune 500 corporation,]] branded the red spoon logo, giving various food-related merchandise the Betty Seal of Approval.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goetz|first1=Kathryn|title=Betty Crocker|url=http://www.mnopedia.org/person/betty-crocker|publisher=MNOPEDIA|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> A portrait of Betty Crocker, first commissioned in 1936 and revised several times since, appears on printed advertisements and product packaging. On television and radio broadcasts, Betty Crocker was portrayed by several actresses, on radio by [[Marjorie Husted]] for twenty years, and on television by [[Adelaide Hawley Cumming]] between 1949 and 1964.\n\nThe character was developed in 1920 as a way to give a personalized response to consumer product questions. The name Betty was selected because it was viewed as a cheery, all-American name.  It was paired with the last name Crocker, in honor of William Crocker, a Washburn Crosby Company director.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Story of Betty Crocker|url=http://www.bettycrocker.com/menus-holidays-parties/mhplibrary/parties-and-get-togethers/vintage-betty/the-story-of-betty-crocker|website=Betty Crocker|publisher=Betty Crocker|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDescribed as an American [[cultural icon]], the image of Betty Crocker has endured several generations, adapting to changing social, political and economic currents.<ref name=\"Adema\">{{cite book|last=Adema |first=Pauline|editor1=Dennis Hall|editor2=Susan G. Hall|title=American Icons: An Encyclopedia of the People, Places, and Things that Have Shaped Our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlxHgYqgDswC&pg=PA73|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-02767-3|pages=73\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{citation | last = Patrick | first = Jeanette | title = Aunt Jemima and Betty Crocker: American Cultural Icons that Never Existed | publisher = [[National Women's History Museum]] | year = 2017 | url = https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/aunt-jemimar-and-betty-crocker}}</ref> Apart from advertising campaigns in printed, broadcast and digital media, she received a number of cultural references in film, literature, music and comics; most notably in the webcomic, [[Homestuck]], as one of the main antagonists. \n\n==Creation==\nBetty Crocker was created in 1921 by [[General Mills|Washburn-Crosby]] and advertiser [[Bruce Fairchild Barton|Bruce Barton]].<ref name=\"Lippy2005\">{{cite book|author=Charles H. Lippy|title=Do Real Men Pray?: Images of the Christian Man and Male Spirituality in White Protestant America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hA85UeTuGzQC&pg=PA133|year=2005|publisher=Univ. of Tennessee Press|isbn=978-1-57233-358-1|pages=133\u2013}}</ref> Under [[Marjorie Husted]]'s supervision, the image of Betty Crocker became the \"Zeus\" of General Mills. In 1921, Washburn Crosby merged with other milling companies to form General Mills.<ref name=\"Adema\"/>\n\nIn 1924, Crocker acquired a voice with the debut of \"The Betty Crocker Cooking School of the Air\" on one station in Minneapolis. It was the country's first radio cooking program. Blanche Ingersoll followed by Husted were selected to portray Betty Crocker. The show proved popular, and eventually was carried nationally on NBC Radio, with Agnes White as Betty. Over the next three decades, the women would anonymously portray Betty Crocker on the air and at cooking schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vchistory.org/people/agnes-white-tizard-betty-crocker/|title=Agnes White Tizard: Betty Crocker|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, Betty Crocker [[coupon]]s were introduced. Inserted in bags of flour, they could be used to reduce the cost of [[Oneida Limited]] [[cutlery|flatware]]. By 1932, this scheme had become so popular that General Mills began to offer an entire set of flatware; the pattern was called \"Friendship\" (later renamed \"Medality\"). In 1937, the coupons were printed on the outside of packages, copy on which told purchasers to \"save and redeem for huge savings on fine kitchen and home accessories in our [[mail-order catalog|catalog]]\".\n\n==Cookbook publications ==\nFrom 1930, General Mills issued softbound recipe books, including in 1933 ''Betty Crocker's 101 Delicious [[Bisquick]] Creations, As Made and Served by Well-Known Gracious Hostesses, Famous Chefs, Distinguished Epicures and Smart Luminaries of Movieland.''{{citation needed|date = January 2012}}\n\n1941\u20131945: The ''Betty Crocker Cook Book of All-Purpose Baking'' was published as an aid to wartime considerations in cooking.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvits|first=Janet|title=Betty Crocker Edition History|url=http://www.cookbookjj.com/college/betty_crocker.htm|publisher=General Mills}}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, the ''Betty Crocker Picture Cookbook'' was published. It was written by nutritionist Agnes White Tizard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alphadeltapi.org/contentmanager/page.asp?webpageid=622|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100905164818/http://www.alphadeltapi.org/contentmanager/page.asp?webpageid=622|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 September 2010|title=Accomplished Alpha Delta Pi Members in Education and Science|accessdate=26 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the 10th edition of the Betty Crocker cookbook was published, as well as a [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[English language|English]] bilingual book that collects some of the more common recipes for Spanish-speaking readers looking to cook American-style food. An 11th edition, in ring-binder format, appeared in 2011. At least 17 other Betty Crocker recipe collections were also in print in 2015. Recipes and collections are also available digitally.<ref>{{cite book|last1=man|first1=VANNY|title=the crokk|publisher=Hannibal}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n''Betty Crocker'' programs first appeared on radio on local stations in 1924. The first network ''Betty Crocker'' broadcast was on [[NBC]] in 1926. The show remained on network radio until 1953; most of the time the program was on NBC or [[CBS]], but it was on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from 1947 to 1953.<ref name=\"dunningota\">{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn |url-access=registration |quote=Betty Crocker, cooking advice. |last1=Dunning |first1=John| title=On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio| date=1998| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=New York, NY| isbn=978-0-19-507678-3| page=[https://archive.org/details/onairencyclop00dunn/page/82 82]| edition=Revised| accessdate=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 1949, the actress [[Adelaide Hawley Cumming]] became Betty Crocker for many years. She appeared for several years on ''[[The George Burns and Gracie Allen Show]]'',<ref name=\"cbsmarks\"/> and even had her own TV show, ''[[Betty Crocker Star Matinee]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McDonough|first1=John|last2=Egolf|first2=Karen|title=The Advertising Age Encyclopedia of Advertising|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135949136|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QpLtCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1280&dq=%22Betty+Crocker+Star+Matinee%22#v=onepage&q=%22Betty%20Crocker%20Star%20Matinee%22&f=false|accessdate=17 October 2017|language=en}}</ref> She also appeared in the [[CBS]] network's first color commercial, in which she baked a \"mystery fruit cake\". Hawley continued to portray Betty Crocker until 1964.<ref>{{cite news|title=Adelaide Hawley Cumming, 93, Television's First Betty Crocker|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/25/arts/adelaide-hawley-cumming-93-television-s-first-betty-crocker.html|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nA portrait of Betty Crocker was first commissioned in 1936,<ref name=drsfsc>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QdwRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Tu8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6657%2C5142832 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=New Betty Crocker dressed for success |date=May 23, 1986 |page=17 }}</ref> a \"motherly image\" that \"blended the features of several Home Service Department members\" that was painted by [[Neysa McMein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saic.edu/150/bold-suffragette-betty-crocker|title=From Bold Suffragette to Betty Crocker - 150 Years of SAIC|author=|date=|website=www.saic.edu|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> It subtly changed over the years, but always accommodated General Mills' cultural perception of the American homemaker&nbsp;\u2014 knowledgeable and caring.<ref name=drsfsc/> The 1996 portrait of Betty Crocker, according to General Mills, was partially inspired by a \"computerized composite\" of \"75 women of diverse backgrounds and ages.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Betty Crocker Portraits|url=http://www.bettycrocker.com/tips/aboutthekitchens/portraits|publisher=General Mills|accessdate=7 January 2013}}</ref>  These portraits were always painted, with no real person ever having posed as a model.{{citation needed|date = January 2012}}\n\nIn 1945, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine named Betty Crocker the second most popular woman in America; [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] was named first.<ref name=\"marks\">{{cite book |isbn=0743265017 |oclc=56880048 |lccn=2004061566 |last=Marks |first=Susan |title=Finding Betty Crocker : the secret life of America's first lady of food |date=2005 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |url=https://archive.org/details/findingbettycroc00mark }}</ref> ''Fortune'' published an article \"outing\" Betty Crocker's fictitious nature, calling her a \"fake\" and a \"fraud.\"{{specify|reason=Was Betty Crocker's outing in the same 1945 Fortune article as the one in which they named Betty Crocker the 2nd most popular woman? CBS source is vague, need to check the details in Marks's book or Fortune's archives.|date=July 2016}}<ref name=\"cbsmarks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/betty-crocker-unveiled/ |title=Betty Crocker Unveiled |last=Dakss|first=Brian |date=May 6, 2005 |newspaper=[[CBS]] |department=[[CBS News Sunday Morning]]}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural References==\n\nIn the multimedia webcomic Homestuck, Betty Crocker is a shady and conspiratorial company owned by who is later revealed to be one of the main antagonists of the story. Like with many other pop-culture references in Homestuck, the brand's cake mix and fruit gushers are initially a running gag. However, as the story grows more complex, so too does Betty Crocker's seemingly insignificant presence, wherein the company's true identity is revealed to be a multiversal, subjugating entity. \n\n==Legacy==\nThe [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]] suburb of [[Golden Valley, Minnesota]] (where General Mills is headquartered) has a street named Betty Crocker Drive.<ref>{{cite web|title=City Streets, Sidewalks, & Trails Map|url=http://www.goldenvalleymn.gov/streets/pdf/streets-trails-walks-map.pdf|website=City of Golden Valley Minnesota|publisher=City of Golden Valley, Minnesota|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of Betty Crocker-branded products, such as plastic food containers and measuring cups, and a line of small appliances like popcorn poppers and sandwich makers with the Betty Crocker brand name.\n\nIn 2006, the Betty Crocker catalog operation went out of business with all of its inventory on sale. Points were redeemable until December 15, 2006. A new online store was launched in April 2007 but discontinued sometime thereafter.\n\nBetty Crocker recipes and tips from the \"Atomic Age\" of the 1950s are of cultural interest.<ref name=NYTM102715>{{cite news|author1=Tamar Adler|title=Betty Crocker's Absurd, Gorgeous Atomic-Age Creations The iconic brand's midcentury recipes evoke the era's peculiar optimism, encased in gelatin and smothered in mayonnaise.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/magazine/betty-crockers-absurd-gorgeous-atomic-age-creations.html|accessdate=November 1, 2015|work=The New York Times Magazine|date=October 27, 2015|quote=segment of American culinary life is on display}}</ref><ref name=BoxOfBetty>{{cite web|title=A Box of Betty|url=http://aboxofbetty.tumblr.com/archive|website=aboxofbetty.tumblr.com|publisher=Tumbir|accessdate=November 1, 2015|format=Images}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n* Bac-Os\n* Betty Crocker Brownie bar\n* [[Betty Crocker Cookbook]]\n* Betty Crocker [[baking mix]]es\n* [[Fruit Roll-Ups]]\n* Betty Crocker canned frosting\n* Bowl Appetit shelf-stable entrees\n* Betty Crocker Soda Licious (discontinued)\n* Cake and dessert decorating products\n* [[Dunkaroos|Dunk-a-roos]]\n* [[Fruit by the Foot]]\n* Fruit Gushers<ref name=\"product catalogue\">[http://www.generalmills.com/Home/Brands/Baking_Products/Betty_Crocker/Brand%20Product%20List%20Page.aspx Betty Crocker product list], General Mills</